07178nam a22010335i 9783110721478DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2022940349  a97831107214787 a10.1515/97831107214782doi  a(DE-B1597)570677  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090002bisacsh00aModality in Underdescribed Languages :bMethods and Insights /ced. by Jozina Vander Klok, Núbia Ferreira Rech, Simone Guesser. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (VI, 423 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs [TiLSM] ,x1861-4302 ;v35700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction to Modality in underdescribed languages: Methods and insights -- tPart I: Contributions of different methods for studying modality -- t1 Fieldwork techniques in semantics -- t2 Studying modality through targeted construction storyboards -- t3 Discourse contexts targeting modality in fieldwork: A revised modal questionnaire -- t4 Using corpora to investigate modal-temporal interactions -- t5 Adapting acquisition methodologies to study modality in underdescribed languages -- tPart II: Lessons from case studies on underdescribed languages -- t6 On applying semantic fieldwork elicitation techniques to describe modality in Ye’kwana -- t7 Modality in elicited data and spontaneous texts: A case study of Atayal -- t8 Lessons from the field: Irrealis mood in Lung’Ie -- t9 Analyzing ʔayʔaǰuθəm evidentials: Evidence for epistemic modality -- t10 Parameters for the production of discourse contexts: Eliciting the semantics of obligations and desires in Mapudungun -- tSubject index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCurrent semantic fieldwork research has shown that the study of modality cannot be conducted via translation alone, yet much of what we know about modal expressions across the world’s language is still translation-based. This book aims to facilitate the study of modality across more diverse languages and a wider participant base by explaining and illustrating a nuanced set of methods, including storyboards, questionnaires, corpora research, experimental tasks, as well as a discussion of practical semantic fieldwork techniques. The methodological protocols tested and employed by the authors on underdescribed languages - spanning seven different language families - are intended to be applicable as cross-linguistic tools, while also indicating the successes and challenges of their contributions. Expanding the study of modality to a wider set of underdescribed languages will undoubtedly bring new insights into our theoretical understanding of modality and deepen our understanding of a cross-linguistic typology of modal expressions.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 4aModalität. 4aMorphosyntax. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  a.  aFieldwork.  aLinguistic Methodology.  aModality.1 aAgostinho, Ana Lívia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Sihwei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCournane, Ailís, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoutinho Costa, Isabella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerreira Rech, Núbia , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFerreira Rech, Núbia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerreira, Luiz Fernando, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuentes, Pablo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuesser, Simone,